1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:03,825
Let's explore ways of fixing some common issues and data.

2
00:00:03,825 --> 00:00:07,025
Here's a toy dataset I created for this lesson.

3
00:00:07,025 --> 00:00:09,240
It has 11 instances of

4
00:00:09,240 --> 00:00:14,805
user product Interactions recording whether the user liked the product,

5
00:00:14,805 --> 00:00:17,565
how long they viewed the product,

6
00:00:17,565 --> 00:00:21,270
whether it was on a website or through a mobile app,

7
00:00:21,270 --> 00:00:24,300
and what time they started viewing the product.

8
00:00:24,300 --> 00:00:29,590
Pause the video and see if you can spot any potential issues in this data.

9
00:00:31,520 --> 00:00:36,900
Let's address three issues in this dataset that are quite common in the real-world.

10
00:00:36,900 --> 00:00:39,075
The first one is missing data,

11
00:00:39,075 --> 00:00:41,970
which we find in the view_duration column.

12
00:00:41,970 --> 00:00:46,295
There are a total of 11 entries or rows in this dataset,

13
00:00:46,295 --> 00:00:50,155
but only eight non-null values in view_duration.

14
00:00:50,155 --> 00:00:52,880
That means there are three no values,

15
00:00:52,880 --> 00:00:54,740
which we can also see here.

16
00:00:54,740 --> 00:00:57,125
This is a small toy dataset.

17
00:00:57,125 --> 00:00:59,645
So we're able to see all the null values here.

18
00:00:59,645 --> 00:01:04,280
But normally you check these values for bigger datasets.

19
00:01:04,280 --> 00:01:07,340
The second issue we'll address is duplicates,

20
00:01:07,340 --> 00:01:10,205
which we find in rows 3 and 4.

21
00:01:10,205 --> 00:01:15,365
Again, we only notice this here because this is a small toy dataset.

22
00:01:15,365 --> 00:01:18,895
I'll show you a better way to check for duplicates in a little bit.

23
00:01:18,895 --> 00:01:22,795
The third issue we'll tackle is incorrect data types.

24
00:01:22,795 --> 00:01:25,790
Here timestamp is represented as

25
00:01:25,790 --> 00:01:30,290
a string when ideally it should be represented as a datetime object.

26
00:01:30,290 --> 00:01:33,320
Remember it says object instead of string here because

27
00:01:33,320 --> 00:01:37,740
pandas stores pointers to strings instead of the strings themselves.

28
00:01:38,060 --> 00:01:42,065
Let's start with the first problem, missing data.

29
00:01:42,065 --> 00:01:47,060
Missing data is an issue that should be handled differently depending on several factors,

30
00:01:47,060 --> 00:01:52,310
such as the reason those values are missing and whether their occurrences seem random.

31
00:01:52,310 --> 00:01:55,850
One way of handling them is imputing them with the mean.

32
00:01:55,850 --> 00:02:00,625
You can do this quickly and efficiently with a convenient function from pandas.

33
00:02:00,625 --> 00:02:04,605
First, let's get the mean of the view_duration column.

34
00:02:04,605 --> 00:02:10,090
Now, let's use pandas fillna function to fill null values with this mean.

35
00:02:10,090 --> 00:02:12,440
Take a look at the DataFrame now.

36
00:02:12,440 --> 00:02:14,345
Does that this fix the problem?

37
00:02:14,345 --> 00:02:17,585
Instead of making changes to the original column,

38
00:02:17,585 --> 00:02:20,510
it actually just returned a new column with the changes,

39
00:02:20,510 --> 00:02:22,195
which we didn't store anywhere.

40
00:02:22,195 --> 00:02:23,630
To keep the changes,

41
00:02:23,630 --> 00:02:26,860
make sure to assign it to the original like this.

42
00:02:26,860 --> 00:02:34,270
Alternatively, you can use a parameter called inplace to make the changes in place.

43
00:02:34,270 --> 00:02:37,625
Awesome, we just fixed our missing data issue.

44
00:02:37,625 --> 00:02:41,195
Next, let's deal with the problem of duplicate data.

45
00:02:41,195 --> 00:02:44,810
There are multiple reasons you may end up with duplicated data,

46
00:02:44,810 --> 00:02:47,890
like combined data sources or human error.

47
00:02:47,890 --> 00:02:50,930
This is a simple scenario where two rows,

48
00:02:50,930 --> 00:02:53,330
3 and 4, are identical.

49
00:02:53,330 --> 00:02:57,290
This toy dataset is small enough for us to count visually.

50
00:02:57,290 --> 00:02:59,180
For bigger datasets, you can use

51
00:02:59,180 --> 00:03:02,330
the duplicated function to see which rows are duplicates.

52
00:03:02,330 --> 00:03:05,300
By default, this marks duplicates as true,

53
00:03:05,300 --> 00:03:07,160
excluding the first instance.

54
00:03:07,160 --> 00:03:12,125
It considers a row to be a duplicate only if the values in all the columns match.

55
00:03:12,125 --> 00:03:15,785
You can change both of these with different parameters.

56
00:03:15,785 --> 00:03:19,010
For larger datasets, it would probably be more

57
00:03:19,010 --> 00:03:22,430
helpful to get a count of the duplicates in the dataset like this.

58
00:03:22,430 --> 00:03:26,690
To drop duplicates, we can use pandas' drop_duplicates function.

59
00:03:26,690 --> 00:03:29,960
Again, we have to use the in-place parameter or assign

60
00:03:29,960 --> 00:03:33,145
the output to the original DataFrame when using this function.

61
00:03:33,145 --> 00:03:35,080
You can see we've dropped ow 4,

62
00:03:35,080 --> 00:03:37,055
the row marked as a duplicate.

63
00:03:37,055 --> 00:03:41,555
Now, this was a simple situation where the entire row was identical.

64
00:03:41,555 --> 00:03:45,910
You can imagine duplicated data scenarios that are a bit more complicated.

65
00:03:45,910 --> 00:03:50,240
For example, let's say we had data on patients from a hospital.

66
00:03:50,240 --> 00:03:53,090
What happens when you come across two rows with

67
00:03:53,090 --> 00:03:57,410
the same patient ID but different data on medical exam results?

68
00:03:57,410 --> 00:03:59,120
Do you combine them,

69
00:03:59,120 --> 00:04:01,380
only keep the latest one?

70
00:04:01,380 --> 00:04:05,045
This is a situation you'd have to investigate more.

71
00:04:05,045 --> 00:04:07,700
For this scenario, you'd likely identify

72
00:04:07,700 --> 00:04:11,525
duplicates only based on the column recording the patients' ID.

73
00:04:11,525 --> 00:04:14,390
You can use a subset parameter in the

74
00:04:14,390 --> 00:04:17,780
duplicated and drop duplicates functions to do this.

75
00:04:17,780 --> 00:04:22,235
Finally, let's address the last issue, incorrect data types.

76
00:04:22,235 --> 00:04:26,720
Incorrect data types is also a problem data analysts frequently come across.

77
00:04:26,720 --> 00:04:31,730
In this case, timestamps are represented as strings instead of date times.

78
00:04:31,730 --> 00:04:34,025
This isn't a critical issue,

79
00:04:34,025 --> 00:04:37,220
but date times are much more convenient to work with if you want to

80
00:04:37,220 --> 00:04:41,060
extract specific information from them or filter them more easily.

81
00:04:41,060 --> 00:04:46,440
Let's use the pandas function to_datetime to convert this column to datetime.

82
00:04:46,990 --> 00:04:51,605
Now we can see timestamp is represented as a date time.

83
00:04:51,605 --> 00:04:56,675
By the way, even if you save this to a CSV file after making this change,

84
00:04:56,675 --> 00:05:00,445
it will also be read as a string by default the next time you open it.

85
00:05:00,445 --> 00:05:02,990
You'd have to convert it again after opening

86
00:05:02,990 --> 00:05:08,450
the CSV file or use parameters like parse dates in the read CSV function.

87
00:05:08,450 --> 00:05:13,040
Although if the strings you have to parse are formatted unconventionally,

88
00:05:13,040 --> 00:05:18,420
the function to_datetime provides more options than the parameters in the read CSV.

